<h2>What Is Somatic Therapy?</h2>
<p>Somatic therapy (from the Greek <em>soma</em>, meaning body) is a broad category of approaches that work with bodily experience — sensation, posture, movement, breath, and nervous system state — as a primary route to psychological healing. It differs from conventional talk therapy, which works primarily through language and cognition.</p>

<p>The foundational premise is that trauma, stress, and emotional experience are not purely mental events — they are stored in and expressed through the body. A person who experienced early trauma may carry it as chronic muscle tension, a collapsed posture, a hyperactive startle response, or a disconnection from bodily sensation. Somatic therapies engage these physical expressions directly.</p>

<h2>The Theoretical Foundation</h2>
<p>Several overlapping scientific foundations support somatic approaches:</p>

<p><strong>Polyvagal Theory</strong> (Stephen Porges) describes how the autonomic nervous system has three hierarchical states — ventral vagal (social safety), sympathetic (fight-or-flight), and dorsal vagal (freeze/collapse) — and how trauma disrupts access to the regulated, social-engagement state. Somatic interventions work to expand the nervous system's capacity for regulation.</p>

<p><strong>Trauma and the Body</strong> (Bessel van der Kolk) articulates how traumatic memory is stored somatically — not as coherent narrative but as fragmented sensory and physical imprints. The phrase "the body keeps the score" captures this: the nervous system retains traumatic experience even when verbal memory is incomplete.</p>

<p><strong>Interoception</strong> — the brain's reading of internal bodily signals — is disrupted by trauma and is a target of somatic approaches. Improving interoception improves emotional awareness and regulation.</p>

<h2>Major Somatic Approaches</h2>

<h3>Somatic Experiencing (SE)</h3>
<p>Developed by Peter Levine, SE tracks bodily sensations as they arise and supports their completion. Animals discharge trauma through physical shaking and trembling after a threat passes; humans often suppress this process. SE facilitates the natural completion of incomplete survival responses, releasing their stored energy from the nervous system.</p>

<h3>EMDR</h3>
<p>EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitisation and Reprocessing) uses bilateral stimulation — typically eye movements — alongside memory processing. It has a significant somatic component in tracking body sensations during processing. EMDR has extensive RCT evidence and WHO endorsement as a trauma treatment.</p>

<h3>Sensorimotor Psychotherapy</h3>
<p>Sensorimotor Psychotherapy integrates somatic awareness with attachment theory and mindfulness. It works with posture, gesture, movement impulses, and sensation as primary therapeutic material alongside verbal processing.</p>

<h3>TRE (Tension and Trauma Releasing Exercises)</h3>
<p>TRE uses a series of exercises to induce neurogenic tremors — the body's natural mechanism for releasing deep muscular tension. It is typically self-administered after initial learning, making it accessible between therapy sessions.</p>

<h2>What Somatic Therapy Looks Like in Practice</h2>
<p>A somatic therapy session involves more attention to what is happening in the body, in the moment, than a traditional talk therapy session. A therapist might ask: "What do you notice in your body as you talk about that?" or "Where do you feel that in your body?" Clients learn to track internal sensation with curiosity rather than anxiety or avoidance.</p>

<p>For trauma, somatic therapy typically involves working at the edges of the trauma — approaching difficult material in small increments and returning to regulated, safe body states — rather than flooding the system with traumatic content.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Is somatic therapy evidence-based?</strong><br/>
Evidence varies by approach. EMDR has the strongest RCT evidence. Somatic Experiencing has growing evidence from RCTs and observational studies. The broader somatic field has less RCT evidence than CBT but is catching up. Polyvagal-informed approaches are increasingly integrated into mainstream trauma treatment.</p>

<p><strong>Who benefits most from somatic therapy?</strong><br/>
People with trauma, particularly when verbal processing has been insufficient. People with chronic stress, chronic pain, or conditions with significant somatic symptoms. People who feel "talked out" — who understand their problems cognitively but can't shift them.</p>

<p><strong>Can somatic therapy be done online?</strong><br/>
Yes. Somatic therapists work online effectively — tracking the client's visible physical presentation, teaching interoceptive awareness, and guiding body-based practices through video. Some hands-on techniques are not available online, but the majority of somatic work translates well.</p>

